snippet.textDisplay:
Question: If an infected person has a very mild expression of the coronavirus infection, will the immune response also be mild?

Or is a mild case a sign the immune response was working so hard the expression of the disease was limited?

Is the immune response the arbitrator of the severity of the disease or are there other factors that cause a mild expression to take place?

Can a mild or asymptomatic carrier have a response so mild the production of antibodies to the virus antigen is an insufficient safeguard to reinfection when the recovered patient comes in contact with the virus again?

Or is a mild or asymptomatic response in one recovered person sufficient to guard against any reinfection of the same virus?

If a "vaccine" is based on using live antiviral components of a human who has successfully recovered from a covid-19 infection, will those components render the virus as a "live virus" type of vaccine? Does that type of vaccine automatically mean the elderly and/or immune compromised people are not good candidates for the vaccine?

If yes, does not that leave many of the most vulnerable unable to be protected by the vaccine?

At what point in the development of pneumonia would live antiviral elements work best?

What are the likely problems of contamination or unintended consequences for a fast tracking of vaccines or treatments using live components?
